Method Call Stack in Exceptions


The method call stack in Java manages method execution and exception handling by creating a stack frame for each method call. When an exception occurs, Java searches upward in the call stack for a matching catch block; otherwise, the program terminates. It helps to:

Trace exception origin and understand exception propagation
Debug runtime errors using stack trace information

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        methodA();
        System.out.println("End of main()");
    }

    static void methodA() {
        methodB();
    }

    static void methodB() {
        int a = 10, b = 0;
        int c = a / b;   // ArithmeticException occurs here
    }
}
Output:

Exception in thread "main" java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero
at Demo.methodB(Main.java:13)
at Demo.methodA(Main.java:8)
at Demo.main(Main.java:3)

Explanation:

main() calls methodA(), which further calls methodB().
methodB() throws an ArithmeticException due to division by zero.
Since methodB() does not handle the exception, Java starts searching backward in the call stack for a matching catch block.
