Work flow of Method Call Stack in Exception
How this Works?
Referring to image above, Execution starts from main(), and each method call adds a new frame (methodB(), methodA()) to the call stack.
When an exception occurs in methodA(), normal execution stops and the exception is thrown.
Java performs stack unwinding, moving upward through the call stack to find a matching catch block.
If a handler is found, the exception is handled and execution resumes; otherwise, the program terminates due to an unhandled exception.
Example 1: Method Call Stack with Caught Exception




class GfG {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            methodA();  // Calling methodA
            System.out.println("Exit main()");
        } catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
            System.out.println("ArithmeticException caught...");
            ex.printStackTrace();  // Prints stack trace for debugging
        }
    }
​
    public static void methodA() {
        System.out.println("Enter methodA()");
        try {
            int a = 5, b = 0;
            int c = a / b;  // Division by zero will throw ArithmeticException
            System.out.println(c);
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("ArithmeticException caught in methodA");
        } finally {
            System.out.println("finally-block runs regardless of the state of exception");
        }
        System.out.println("Exit methodA()");
    }
}

Output
Enter methodA()
ArithmeticException caught in methodA
finally-block runs regardless of the state of exception
Exit methodA()
Exit main()
Explanation:

The program starts execution from main(), which calls methodA() inside a try block.
In methodA(), division by zero throws an ArithmeticException, which is caught within methodA() itself.
The finally block in methodA() executes regardless of the exception and then the method completes execution.
Control returns to main(), and since the exception was already handled, Exit main() is printed.
Example 2: Uncaught Exception Propagation




public class ExceptionDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            methodA();  // Calling methodA
        } catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
            System.out.println("ArithmeticException caught in main()");
            ex.printStackTrace();
        } finally {
            System.out.println("finally in main() - executed after try-catch");
        }
    }
​
    public static void methodA() {
        System.out.println("Enter methodA()");
        int a = 5, b = 0;
        int c = a / b;  // This will throw ArithmeticException
        System.out.println(c);
    }
}
Output:

java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero
at ExceptionDemo.methodA(ExceptionDemo.java:16)
at ExceptionDemo.main(ExceptionDemo.java:4)

Explanation:

The program starts from main(), which calls methodA() inside a try block.
In methodA(), division by zero causes an ArithmeticException, and since there is no try-catch, the exception is not handled there.
The exception propagates back to main(), where it is caught by the catch block and the stack trace is printed.
The finally block in main() executes after exception handling, ensuring cleanup before program termination.
